Alcmena's warlike son The thorny course of virtue

the glorious choice : Severe , indeed , the attempt he knew , Youth's genial ardours to subdue : For Pleasure Cytherea's form assumed , Her glowing charms divinely bright , In all the pride of beauty bloomed , And struck his ravished sight
the Elysian bower : Her hand , that trembling ardours move
wake the slumbering sparks of fame , To kindle and arouse the dying flame
Ah ! shall that soft delicious chain The godlike victim thus enslave ; Kind heaven his sinking soul sustain , And from perdition snatch the brave ! — By heavenly mandate Virtue
Her form transcendent shine With majesty divine
heart a sacred impulse swayed : His eyes with eager tumult roll , As on each rival-nymph they bend , While love , regret , and hope divide his soul By turns , and with conflicting anguish rend
the soft inglorious reign : Convinced , resolved , to Virtue then he turned , And in his breast paternal glory burned

him the royal youth she won : Thus taught , he flies the peaceful shore , And bids our warlike fleet advance , The hostile squadrons to explore , To kerb the powers of Spain and France : Aloft his martial ensigns flow
the main , Extend the embattled line
Hark ! hark ! their shouts arise , And shake the vaulted skies
Neptune that standard revere , Whose power is superior to thine !
All dissonant strife they disclaim ; And only are rivals in fame
For thee , the Muse awakes her artless lays , For thee her harp spontaneous plays The tribute of a soul sincere
